post_text:
USDA has approved a waiver allowing ALL students to eat lunch at no cost. No paperwork, no applications, all students are immediately eligible! This waiver went into effect September 1 and runs through December 31, 2020. Meals from yesterday and today will be credited to student lunch accounts. Any extra items, milk or THS a la cart, will still need to be purchased.

We anticipate no cost to the District as all student meals will be reimbursed through the USDA, just as they were this past spring.

If you have questions, please contact Norma Koester, Food Service Director, at 217-857-3535.

post_text:
The First Day of School for K-12th grade is Friday, August 14th. Due to COVID-19, parents will not be allowed in TGS to walk their children to the classrooms. 1st-6th grade students will report to the gym and will be assisted by TGS staff to find their classrooms and help with transitions. Kindergarten teachers have a plan for the first day to help with transitions which will be shared at Kindergarten Orientation on the Lawn,Tuesday, August 11 at 6:00pm .

Dismissal will be as follows on Friday:

11:35 a.m.-Early Buses

11:40 a.m.-Parent Pick-Up and Walkers- Parent Pick-Up is at the East circle drive. Please enter from the North. All cars should exit to the South and proceed over the railroad tracks to assist with traffic flow.

11:45 a.m.-Late Buses

Please contact the TGS office if you have any further questions.

Wooden Shoe families, please check your TeacherEase email for an UPDATED Return to School Plan!

Today's communication has several important updates:
1) 2:30 Early Dismissal on Mondays & Tuesdays
2) Symptom Screening Update
3) Student Confidentiality & Digital Content Update
4) Responding to Confirmed Case or Symptomatic Student/Staff

We understand that some of these updates may complicate matters for our families. In working with our staff, and with the increase in Covid positive cases and self-isolations in the county, we believe that these updates continue to prioritize student and staff safety, social-emotional health, academic achievement, and the needs of our families and community.

Stay tuned for additional developments and call Mr. Sturgeon at the Unit Office with questions!

Every year, the Illinois State Board of Education (ISBE) surveys a representative sample of parents of students with disabilities to determine how well schools throughout the state are involving parents in their children’s education. This year, parents of students with special education needs in Teutopolis school district may receive a survey. Parents may complete the paper survey and return it by mail or complete it online at www.mievaluation.com/isbe2020.htm. Please consider taking the time to complete this survey. Thank you!

ISBE Flyer 2020: https://bit.ly/2UmAhF6

Message from THS Senior Parents:
There will be a parade through town to honor our THS Seniors on Sunday, May 17 beginning at 5:00 p.m.!

It will begin at Teutopolis High School and proceed south on Race St.
East on Elm St.
North on Pearl St.
Cross HWY 40 - and go west on Walnut St.
South on Race St. - back to THS.
Please respect all social distancing guidelines.

Senior parents - please decorate your vehicles and be ready to escort your graduate in the parade!
Meet at THS student parking lot (east side) at 4:45 p.m.

We hope to have our community line the streets and decorate their yards to support our graduates!

To: All THS Seniors and Senior Parents
From: Deb Philpot, Interim Supt.
Subject: Virtual Graduation and Traditional Graduation
Good evening! Mrs. Mapes sent an email through Teacher Ease to all seniors and senior parents this evening. Please look for this email as it contains guidance regarding the upcoming virtual graduation ceremony and what we need from seniors and senior parents. The email also provides information regarding virtual senior honors night and what is needed from each senior.
Staff are working hard to put together a virtual graduation ceremony that will be very memorable for our seniors. I do want to remind everyone that it is the district’s intent to host a traditional ceremony at a later date. That date has not been established yet, but seniors and parents will be notified when it is.
Please let us know if you have further questions once you read Mrs. Mapes’ email. THANK YOU!

Teutopolis High School Graduation Announcement:
Due to the Governor's Stay at Home Order being extended through May 30th we will be postponing our traditional High School Graduation Ceremony to a later date after the Stay at Home Order is lifted. HOWEVER, Teutopolis School District is pleased to announce that we will be honoring the THS Class of 2020 on May 24th when Teutopolis School District premieres its first ever Teutopolis High School Virtual Graduation Ceremony. THS Staff will be working with senior students and senior parents to prepare an online ceremony to honor our seniors on May 24th. Senior students and families, please be checking your emails for information forthcoming. Please mark your calendars to attend the THS Class of 2020 Virtual High School Graduation on May 24th. Further online airing details, and premiere time will be announced at a later date.

post_text:
TGS Parents
Regarding materials pick-up on Monday, March 30:

Pick-up will be from 3:00-6:00 p.m. in the front circle drive.
As you pull into the drive, be prepared to share your last name and the first names of all your TGS students with the staff member there.
After giving your name, please pull as far forward as possible as you advance through the drive.
Staff members will come to your vehicle with your child's materials.
Students in grades 2-6 will be receiving their Chromebooks.
At pick-up, please return your child's current completed packet.
All children will be receiving new library books.
At pick-up, you may return any current library books you would like to discard.
Thank you all so much for your overwhelming support. As we begin these "Remote Instructional Days", do not hesitate to reach out with questions as the curriculum will have more rigor. We are all finding our way in these unusual times.

post_text:
We would like to take this time to thank the school board, administration, parents and students for being so amazing. We also want to thank all the wonderful faculty and staff we have the absolute privilege of working with. You folks are the BEST!! These last few days have been a whirlwind and the next few weeks will be trying to say the least. But there is no doubt that we will all get through this and will definitely be stronger because of it. We would especially like to thank all our students at the high school. We have witnessed over and over how these kids help each other, protect each other, and rise up when they need to. As educators, moms, and one soon-to-be grandma, it gives us great comfort in knowing that our world is surrounded by such amazing young people. Thank you for this. Now enough of the mushy stuff…it’s still a school day so to our Psychology and Health students…work on your packets! And we miss all of you!
Mrs. Grinestaff and Mrs. Hall

post_text: Good afternoon! This is Deborah Philpot, Superintendent. As of 3:30 pm today in a phone conference call to all superintendents Governor JB Pritzker announced that he is closing all Illinois schools from Tuesday, March 17 until Monday, March 30. We will be holding School on Monday, March 16. On Monday we will be sending students home with a large amount of school materials. We hope to provide educational programming to students while they are at home through learning packets and or E-learning lessons. These Learning materials may not all be distributed on Monday but at a later date. I apologize for this late notice but as I mentioned earlier we were notified of this closure at 3:30 PM today. I will continue to provide you updates as I deem appropriate. Again school will be closing from Tuesday, March 17 until Monday, March 30. Thank you.

post_text:
On March 4th, 6th-grade student Madison Miller was honored at the St. Louis Powell Symphony Hall. Madison was one of one hundred students to receive an award for her artwork. Students in general music listened to Waltz from Khachaturian's Masquerade Suite as the inspiration for their art. The top seven pictures, one from each grade level, were sent to St. Louis to be judged. Congratulations to Madison Miller for being chosen for this honor!

Madison is shown with her music teacher, Ms. Brown.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A-k_loiBYI8&feature=emb_logo

post_text:
Dear Parents and Guardians,

I am writing to address an incident today at Teutopolis High School involving police and assure you that your child is safe and not in danger.

The police were at the high school because the district notified law enforcement of a possible inappropriate social media contact with a student and adult male. The adult male — who is not an employee of Teutopolis School District and does not reside in this area — was taken into custody in the parking lot by police.

The safety of our students and staff is our top priority, and I want to assure you that at no point did the adult male come into contact with any other students at the high school today.

Because this is an ongoing criminal investigation, I cannot comment further at this time.

A potential serious situation was avoided today due to several of our students stepping forward with information and looking out for their fellow students. We are grateful for our students looking out for one another!

Thank you for your support of our students.

Sincerely,
Deborah Philpot
Superintendent

post_text: The students in Mrs. Jansen's kindergarten class try to "Save Sam". Sam the gummy snake never learned how to swim. Sam's boat capsized. Students used cups as Sam's boat, gummy circles for Sam's life preserver, and gummy worms for Sam. The children could only use a paper clip to help get Sam into his life preserver. The students enjoyed working together to complete this challenge.
